<article>
    <h1>Na&#xAD;ture calls in the north</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Make your first stop Fu Shan Gar­den (81 Wood­lands Street 81) in an ex­cur­sion up north. It is a di­nosaur-themed play­ground my four-year-old child Elna was bent on vis­it­ing af­ter see­ing it in a pre-school mag­a­zine.</p>
    <p>We even­tu­ally paid a surprise visit, com­bined with a visit to Ad­mi­ralty Park Play­ground</p>
    <p>(6A Ad­mi­ralty Road), when I re­alised the two play­grounds are a mere 15 min­utes’ walk apart.</p>
    <p>Ad­mi­ralty Park Play­ground is so huge, par­ents will get a work­out just trail­ing the kids. Note that the two long roller slides – my favourite ones – at the Ad­ven­ture Play sec­tion are closed un­til Dec 31.</p>
    <p>We dis­cov­ered the Walk­ing Trail at Ad­mi­ralty Park by ac­ci­dent, while try­ing to make our way to our lunch spot 20 min­utes away by foot. The trail is mostly on flat ground and leads through a sec­ondary for­est and a man­grove swamp along Sungei Cina.</p>
    <p>Do al­lo­cate more time if you want to go on the man­grove board­walk. The crowds even­tu­ally thin off, a much-wel­comed respite af­ter see­ing one too many scream­ing kids.</p>
    <p>Perched on Wood­lands Jetty over­look­ing the Straits of Jo­hor, Rasa Is­timewa Wa­ter­front Restau­rant (6A Ad­mi­ralty Road West) is a no-frills zi char eatery with de­lec­ta­ble fried baby squid, stir-fried lala and seafood sam­bal chilli noo­dles (above).</p>
    <p>You can walk off your lunch at Wood­lands Wa­ter­front Park (Ad­mi­ralty Road West).</p>

